"{\n  \"type\": \"theorem\",\n  \"name\": \"Maximum Distance on Ellipsoid\",\n  \"hypothesis\": [],\n  \"conclusion\": \"The points (1, 0, 0) and (-1, 0, 0) on the ellipsoid  \\( x^{2}+2 y^{2}+3 z^{2}=1 \\) have the largest distance from the origin.\",\n  \"status\": \"proved\",\n  \"proof\": {\n    \"type\": \"proof\",\n    \"steps\": [\n      {\n        \"type\": \"remark\",\n        \"statement\": \"We will use the method of Lagrange multipliers to maximize the distance from the origin subject to the constraint of being on the ellipsoid.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"let\",\n        \"variable\": \"f(x,y,z)\",\n        \"value\": \"x^2 + y^2 + z^2\",\n        \"kind\": \"function\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"remark\",\n        \"statement\": \"Note that maximizing \\(f(x,y,z)\\) is equivalent to maximizing the distance from the origin.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"let\",\n        \"variable\": \"g(x,y,z)\",\n        \"value\": \"x^2 + 2y^2 + 3z^2 - 1\",\n        \"kind\": \"function\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"remark\",\n        \"statement\": \"The ellipsoid is defined by the equation g(x,y,z) = 0.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"assume\",\n        \"statement\": \"There exists a point (x,y,z) on the ellipsoid where f(x,y,z) is maximized.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"assert\",\n        \"claim\": \"There exists a real number \\\\lambda such that  ∇f = λ∇g at the point (x,y,z).\",\n        \"deduced_from\": [\"Method of Lagrange Multipliers\"],\n        \"proof-method\": \"This is a direct consequence of the method of Lagrange multipliers.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"assert\",\n        \"claim\": \"2(x, y, z) = λ(2x, 4y, 6z)\",\n        \"proof-method\": \"Computing the gradients of f and g.\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"cases\",\n        \"on\": \"x\",\n        \"split-kind\": \"condition\",\n        \"proof-cases\": [\n          {\n            \"type\": \"case\",\n            \"condition\": \"x = 0\",\n            \"proof\": {\n              \"type\": \"proof\",\n              \"steps\": [\n                {\n                  \"type\": \"assert\",\n                  \"claim\": \"y = z = 0\",\n                  \"proof-method\": \"From the equation 2(x, y, z) = λ(2x, 4y, 6z) and x=0, we get y = z = 0.\"\n                },\n                {\n                  \"type\": \"assert\",\n                  \"claim\": \"This contradicts the fact that (x,y,z) lies on the ellipsoid.\",\n                  \"proof-method\": \"The point (0,0,0) does not satisfy the equation of the ellipsoid.\"\n                }\n              ]\n            }\n          },\n          {\n            \"type\": \"case\",\n            \"condition\": \"x != 0\",\n            \"proof\": {\n              \"type\": \"proof\",\n              \"steps\": [\n                {\n                  \"type\": \"assert\",\n                  \"claim\": \"λ = 1\",\n                  \"proof-method\": \"From the equation 2(x, y, z) = λ(2x, 4y, 6z) and x != 0, we can divide the first component by 2x to get λ = 1.\"\n                },\n                {\n                  \"type\": \"assert\",\n                  \"claim\": \"y = z = 0\",\n                  \"proof-method\": \"Substituting λ = 1 into the equation 2(x, y, z) = λ(2x, 4y, 6z), we get y = z = 0.\"\n                },\n                {\n                  \"type\": \"assert\",\n                  \"claim\": \"(x,y,z) = (1,0,0) or (-1,0,0)\",\n                  \"proof-method\": \"Substituting y = z = 0 into the equation of the ellipsoid, we get x^2 = 1.\"\n                }\n              ]\n            }\n          }\n        ]\n      },\n      {\n        \"type\": \"conclude\",\n        \"statement\": \"The only points on the ellipsoid where the distance from the origin can be maximized are (1, 0, 0) and (-1, 0, 0). Since the distance from the origin to these two points is the same, they both represent points of maximum distance.\"\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n"